A workload is memory-intensive when it stores or holds large amounts of data in RAM.
A workload is compute-intensive when it spends most of its time performing CPU-heavy calculations.

General Purpose
Balanced CPU, memory, and network performance — good for many common workloads such as small-medium web servers, app servers, or development/test environments.

Compute Optimized
Designed for CPU-heavy workloads where processing power is more important than memory. Great for high-performance web servers, batch jobs, scientific modeling, and HPC tasks

Memory Optimized
More memory relative to CPU — ideal for memory-intensive workloads like large databases, in-memory caches, and real-time analytics

Storage Optimized
For workloads that need very fast local storage, especially with heavy read/write operations — like databases, big data, and log processing

Accelerated Computing
Include specialized hardware like GPUs, FPGAs, or custom accelerators to speed up certain tasks — especially useful for AI/ML, graphics, simulations, and data pattern matching.

